  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Education system of India before the arrival of Britishers?",
  "response": "Before the arrival of the British, the education system in India was quite diverse and had a rich tradition that catered to various strata of society.\n\n### Ancient and Medieval Education System:\n1. **Gurukula System**:\n   - The Gurukula system was prevalent where students, often boys, lived with their guru (teacher) in his home or ashram.\n   - Education included various subjects like literature, mathematics, astronomy, medicine, philosophy, ethics, and physical education.\n   - The focus was not only on academic learning but also on the holistic development of the individual, including their moral, ethical, and spiritual growth.\n   - Teaching was mainly verbal and included memorization, discussion, and practical application.\n\n2. **Centers of Higher Learning**:\n   - Renowned universities and centers of learning such as Taxila, Nalanda, Vikramashila, and others attracted scholars from all over the world.\n   - These institutions were known for their rigorous academics and comprehensive curricula covering numerous fields of study including theology, philosophy, arts, sciences, and medicine.\n   - Prolific teachers and scholars contributed to the global knowledge pool through extensive writings and discourses.\n\n3. **Temple and Monastery Schools**:\n   - Temples and monasteries served as educational centers where monks and priests taught students.\n   - These schools offered education in religious texts, philosophy, rituals, language, and local arts and sciences.\n   - As centers of cultural and intellectual exchange, they played a vital role in preserving and disseminating knowledge.\n\n4. **Madrasahs and Maktabs**:\n   - In regions influenced by Islam, education was focused in madrasahs and maktabs, which provided instruction in the Qur'an, Hadiths, Islamic theology, jurisprudence, and linguistics.\n   - These institutions often incorporated subjects such as mathematics, astronomy, and medicine.\n\n### Characteristics of Pre-British Education:\n- **Inclusivity**: Educational opportunities were accessible to a wide range of people, though certain systems emphasized the education of boys more than girls.\n- **Localized and Decentralized**: Education was community-centric, decentralized, and highly localized. Each region had its unique system that catered to its societal needs.\n- **Holistic Education**: The focus extended beyond academic knowledge to include physical, moral, and spiritual training.\n- **Emphasis on Oral Tradition**: Much of the education was delivered orally, relying on memorization and recitation. Written texts were used but less widely than verbal instruction.\n- **Diverse Curriculum**: Different schools offered a variety of subjects, including secular and religious teachings, without any standardized curriculum across the subcontinent.\n\nOverall, the education system in India before the British was rich in tradition and varied regionally, supporting both intellectual and spiritual development.",
